        "trailText":"More than 120 MPs including former ministers support motion criticising Northern Ireland attorney general's decision",
        "headline":"Peter Hain backed by MPs after he is prosecuted for criticising judge",
        "body":"<p>Just over 120 MPs including Alistair Darling, David Davis and David Blunkett are to criticise the Northern Ireland attorney general for seeking to <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2012/mar/27/peter-hain-contempt-case-judge\" title=\"\">prosecute Peter Hain</a> for the ancient offence of scandalising the court.</p><p>Hain, who is being prosecuted over remarks criticising a high court judge in his book <a href=\"http://www.guardianbookshop.co.uk/BerteShopWeb/viewProduct.do?ISBN=9781849541183\" title=\"\">Outside In</a>, is also expected to receive support from the former Liberal Democrat leader Charles Kennedy and two fellow former Northern Ireland secretaries, Sean Woodward and Paul Murphy.</p><p>Two senior figures on the Conservative right, Peter Lilley and John Redwood, are also expected to put their name to an early day motion (EDM) criticising John Larkin, the Northern Ireland attorney general.</p><p>In the Commons on Wednesday, <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2012/apr/18/cameron-backs-hain-judges-memoir\" title=\"\">David Cameron expressed his sympathy with the plight of Hain</a>.</p><p>The EDM, organised by Davis, a former shadow home secretary, describes the case as a \"deeply disturbing use of the ancient offence of 'abusing a judge'\", considered obsolete since the end of the 19th century.</p><p>It calls upon Larkin to \"end immediately this serious attack on free speech by withdrawing the proceedings for contempt, further asserts the fundamental right of members of this house to express their views responsibly without fear of such judicial censorship, and asks Mr Speaker to consider what action the house might take to defend its rights against such attacks\".</p><p>Davis said: \"This case shows the attorney general deeply out of touch on the right of parliamentarians to express their views freely, and also out of touch on what public opinion regards as fair use of colloquialisms in a book.</p><p>\"Politicians have a right to be critical of the decisions of the judiciary and home secretaries including Blunkett have frequently been so, often to express the views of the public.\"</p><p>In his book, Hain criticised Lord Justice Girvan for agreeing to a judicial review to prevent the appointment of Bertha MacDougall to oversee a victims' commission in Northern Ireland.</p><p>The free speech issue was raised by Blunkett at prime minister's questions in the Commons.</p><p>In a question to Cameron, Blunkett said: \"Shouldn't respect for the independence of the judiciary be balanced by the rights of individuals to fair comment on that judiciary?\"</p><p>Larkin has been granted leave to prosecute Hain and the book's publisher, Biteback, over claims that a strongly worded passage in his memoir \"undermines the administration of justice\".</p><p>Cameron said MPs should be free to criticise the judiciary, just as judges should be allowed to attack politicians.</p><p>The prime minister said: \"Parliamentary privilege obviously quite rightly allows MPs to express their views in parliament.</p><p>\"In terms of what is said outside parliament, let me just say this: there are occasions we all know when judges make critical remarks about politicians and there are occasionally [times] when politicians make critical remarks about judges.</p><p>\"To me, this is part of life in a modern democracy and I think we should try to keep these things as far as possible out of the courts.\"</p><p>A Downing Street spokeswoman said his remarks represented his view that judges should be able to take criticism, but he did not believe he had the power to order the case to be stopped. The decision had not been taken by a minister, she said.</p><p>Hain has vowed to defend free speech against what his publisher said was an arcane law banning criticism of judges, which had not been used in living memory.</p><p>Hain's remarks about Girvan caused controversy in Belfast when the book was published.</p><p>The lord chief justice, Sir Declan Morgan, described them as \"potentially an assault on the wider independence of the judiciary\".</p><p>Hain declined to back down and renewed his criticism, sparking the legal action by Larkin. The case is listed for review by the divisional court in Belfast on 24 April.</p><p>The attorney general's court submission claimed Hain's remarks \"constitute unwarranted abuse of a judge in his judicial capacity that undermines the administration of justice in this jurisdiction, and consequently constitute a contempt of court\".</p><p>The statement added that the book \"create[s] without justification a real risk that public confidence will be undermined in the judiciary\".</p><p>Hain said in a statement at the time of the attorney general's decision: \"I am astonished at this turn of events. I worked harder than anyone as secretary of state for Northern Ireland to uphold the rule of law and judicial independence and delivered the 2007 settlement which helped secure that.</p><p>\"If free speech and comment in a political memoir is to be suppressed then people will be entitled to ask: what system of justice prevails?\"</p><p>Judges such as Lord Justice Sedley have successfully prosecuted newspapers for libel and have sometimes complained that they are shackled combatants on issues of public controversy.</p><div class=\"gu_advert\">\n        <iframe marginheight=\"0\" scrolling=\"NO\" width=\"300px\" marginwidth=\"0\" src=\"http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/politics&k=Peter+Hain&k=Northern+Ireland&k=Judiciary&k=Freedom+of+speech&k=Politics&k=UK+news\" style=\"border: none\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"250px\">\n          <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/politics/oas.html/@Bottom\">\n              <img alt=\"Ads by The Guardian\" src=\"http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/politics/oas.html/@Bottom\"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src='http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Peter+Hain+backed+by+MPs+after+he+is+prosecuted+for+criticising+judge+Article+1733494&ch=Politics&c2=148491&c4=Peter+Hain%2CNorthern+Ireland+%28News%29%2CJudiciary%2CFreedom+of+speech+%28News%29%2CPolitics%2CUK+news%2CLaw%2CWorld+news&c3=guardian.co.uk&c6=Patrick+Wintour&c7=12-Apr-19&c8=1733494&c9=Article' width='1' height='1' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: politics/2012/apr/19/peter-hain-mps-prosecuted-judge|2012-04-20T09:42:55Z|10994366911764a6647a97b0d9ebf70a65e0fb0a -->",
