        "newspaperPageNumber":"9",
        "trailText":"Retired teacher Patricia Watt says she hopes to find closure over death of steward George MacKie",
        "headline":"Titanic Memorial Cruise passenger remembers grandfather",
        "body":"<p>At 2.20am on Sunday, 1,309 passengers aboard MS Balmoral on the Titanic Memorial Cruise will be at the very spot the White Star Line's \"unsinkable ship\" sank 100 years ago. Among those re-creating the journey, and the atmosphere prior to the tragedy, is Patricia Watt, 81, a retired teacher from Bristol, travelling with her husband, David, 80, and who hopes to find \"closure\" at a simple onboard service to commemorate the 1,514 who died.</p><p>\"My grandfather, on my mother's side, was a steward on the Titanic. He was second class steward George MacKie, aged 34, from Southampton. And he went down with the ship.</p><p>\"It wasn't something we talked about early on. My grandmother was left with three young children to bring up, so it took a while before we knew much about it.</p><p>\"I just thought, being here and doing this, would be closure for my family, because my grandmother was never able, obviously, to hold a funeral service for her husband.</p><p>\"I've brought a photograph of him with me, because there may be people on board who wish to know what he was like.</p><p>\"I saw the advert for the cruise about two or three years ago. I'd always wanted to do something to acknowledge my grandfather, and I was very pleased there would be the opportunity to visit the wreck site.</p><p>\"There are quite a few people on board who have family links. We are all sharing our experiences and family histories. It's not sadness so much as having something in common with other passengers. That's been quite important.</p><p>\"There's something like 44 people who are descendants. And there are people who have taken an interest in the Titanic over many years. On the whole, those on board are people who have a very strong interest either through family or through studying what happened.</p><p>\"It's a very friendly atmosphere. You start talking to other passengers and asking them why they are here, which is perhaps something you wouldn't normally do on a cruise. And I've found others who have very similar stories to mine.</p><p>\"There are some fantastic outfits. Some people have gone to great lengths - wonderful hats and dresses and clothes from the Edwardian era. It's fun. I've not done a great deal, but everyone is trying to get into what the atmosphere would have been like, obviously, prior to things going wrong. People are entering into the spirit. I've brought formal evening wear \u2013 I've got a long dress and jacket. And a tiara, though not a real one. I've also got a fur stole, just to be a little bit elegant, as they would have been.</p><p>\"Each evening there is always one dish available that would have been served on the Titanic. Last night it was chicken and rice, which would have been served to second class passengers. The first night there was cabbage with cheese sauce, which was on the original menu.</p><p>\"And the music is also what would have been played on board. The musicians are dressed in the evening suits that the orchestra would have worn on the White Star Line.</p><p>\"I've spent the days going to some very enjoyable talks about the Titanic by people who have done a lot of research. One was by a great granddaughter of one of the passengers, and another by a grandson of a steward who had survived.</p><p>\"I think what has surprised me, the more I've learned, is the distinction between the classes. The class system was very much more in evidence than perhaps we realised. There were many on board who were actually extremely wealthy, and there was a very big difference between them and the working class. .</p><p>\"When we get to the wreck site, there will be some sadness. But I think also some sense of release. And I shall feel a sense of accomplishment that I have achieved what I set out to achieve.</p><p>\"I think the service will be a very memorable occasion, slightly sad, but also for a lot of people it will be the event of the cruise.</p><p>\"I will think of my grandfather. But also my grandmother, who was left with three young children. She had a very difficult life. She really struggled and it wasn't easy. But she was always a very gracious lady. We didn't get the impression that she had any bitterness about the tragedy. Yes, I shall think very much about her.\"</p><div class=\"gu_advert\">\n        <iframe marginheight=\"0\" scrolling=\"NO\" width=\"300px\" marginwidth=\"0\" src=\"http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/uk&k=The+Titanic&k=UK+news&k=World+news\" style=\"border: none\" frameborder=\"0\" height=\"250px\">\n          <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/uk/oas.html/@Bottom\">\n              <img alt=\"Ads by The Guardian\" src=\"http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/uk/oas.html/@Bottom\"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src='http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Titanic+Memorial+Cruise+passenger+remembers+grandfather+Article+1731165&ch=UK+news&c2=148491&c4=Titanic+%28News%29%2CUK+news%2CWorld+news&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Caroline+Davies&c7=12-Apr-13&c8=1731165&c9=Article' width='1' height='1' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: uk/2012/apr/13/titanic-memorial-cruise-passenger|2012-04-20T09:43:57Z|ee48e677bfc45578ca0c72ab1d607271030e8174 -->",
